<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<!-- See "Creating Events and Sectors" guide for MV 5.4+ by Kix.

=== Making your Sector Appear ===
If you are working with vanilla, making your sector spawn is very easy. 
You simply have to append it to one of the following lists; 
CIVILIAN
HOSTILE
NEBULA
This will determine the color of the sector as well.

If you are making a sector for MV, its slightly more complicated. In order to set the color of your sector you will 
still need to append it to one of the above lists, with the except of neutral (grey) sectors.

To make your sector appear however, you will need to append it to one or more of the following lists as well;
ZONE_SAFE
SECTOR_LIST_ALLIED
SECTOR_LIST_NEUTRAL
SECTOR_LIST_HOSTILE
SECTOR_LIST_GENERIC
SECTOR_LIST_UNIQUE_SAFE
SECTOR_LIST_UNIQUE_DEADLY

If you are making a unique sector, you should only ever add it to the last two lists. These sectors are used to 
determine the "zones" on MV's sector map. I would recommend looking at the top of MV's sector_data.xml.append file to 
understand the spawn logic.

The one exception to all of this is SECRET sectors, which do not need to be appended to ANY lists. This guide will not go 
into the details of secret sectors however, but keep in mind it is impossible to make a custom secret sector without Hyperspace.


=== MAKING A SECTOR ===
(...)
Then, finally, we have the actual events. The startEvent tag defines the first event you encounter when entering the sector. 
If you are making your mod for MV, you'll want to take a look at the atlas mechanic in events_special_lightspeed.xml.append 
and replicate the structure there.

The following event tags allow you to define the events that can appear in the sector and the amount that the sector will 
try to spawn. While you can set an individual event to spawn using these, most events are provided using an eventList. 
This allows you to randomize the events that can spawn in your sector. 

In order to prevent an event from spawning multiple times in your sector, you must give it the unique attribute. For example;
<event name="COOL_EVENT" unique="true">

Be very careful with unique events however. If your eventList has 7 unique events in it, but your sector asks for 8 events 
from that list - the game WILL CRASH, as there are not enough events it can spawn.

Events are spawned in the order that they are included in the list, with the exception of nebula events. 
Events/eventLists prefixed with NEBULA_ will always spawn before any other events. 
The order of events included in the above example is the typical order for MV. Most MV sectors also have 
the bonus PIRACY_LIST and FILLER_LIST eventLists included at the very bottom, which are identical for every sector. 
These help fill in any gaps and are usually just very generic all-purpose events.
-->


